00:45:35.277 --> 00:45:37.110
AUDIENCE: She's a really
hard act to follow,

00:45:37.110 --> 00:45:39.360
but at least I have gray hair.

00:45:39.360 --> 00:45:42.770
I have one comment
and then a question.

00:45:42.770 --> 00:45:48.160
My comment is I'm 61, and
I'm a professor at Stanford.

00:45:48.160 --> 00:45:51.670
This is the first time I've
ever gotten up to a microphone

00:45:51.670 --> 00:45:52.755
to ask a question.

00:45:57.910 --> 00:46:00.190
And I noticed the
reason I got up

00:46:00.190 --> 00:46:03.150
is because of the first
four people who got up,

00:46:03.150 --> 00:46:05.160
three were men and
one was a woman,

00:46:05.160 --> 00:46:09.030
and I said, I have to
get up and say that.

00:46:09.030 --> 00:46:12.110
Because even in this
audience, the men

00:46:12.110 --> 00:46:15.370
were quicker on
the draw and felt

00:46:15.370 --> 00:46:19.440
more legitimate about
jumping up to ask a question.

00:46:19.440 --> 00:46:22.140
And I think that
that says something

00:46:22.140 --> 00:46:25.840
about what is the
underlying set of issues.

00:46:25.840 --> 00:46:28.070
And now my question, which
relates to the underlying

00:46:28.070 --> 00:46:34.420
set of issues, which
is that what I'm seeing

00:46:34.420 --> 00:46:37.970
among the young people,
who I'm teaching

00:46:37.970 --> 00:46:40.960
and who I'm seeing
through my children,

00:46:40.960 --> 00:46:48.210
is that young women, many of
whom have had feminist mothers,

00:46:48.210 --> 00:46:53.960
are seeing how difficult it
is to, quote, "have it all."

00:46:53.960 --> 00:46:58.430
And that working full-time
and having quality time

00:46:58.430 --> 00:47:01.390
with their children-- which
is all the stuff that they're

00:47:01.390 --> 00:47:04.000
hearing-- just seems impossible.

00:47:04.000 --> 00:47:06.610
And I think indeed, it is.

00:47:06.610 --> 00:47:10.690
And what is not
happening is the men

00:47:10.690 --> 00:47:14.640
are not feeling
that they dare risk

00:47:14.640 --> 00:47:18.590
their careers to be at home.

00:47:21.880 --> 00:47:24.750
Betty Friedan had
said that that's

00:47:24.750 --> 00:47:27.090
where the problem
is, that we have not

00:47:27.090 --> 00:47:32.040
changed the cultural
view of what a family is,

00:47:32.040 --> 00:47:33.910
of what men should do.

00:47:33.910 --> 00:47:35.210
You've talked about it.

00:47:35.210 --> 00:47:41.520
But I ask if you have any
ideas about how to really begin

00:47:41.520 --> 00:47:47.340
to allow men to be at home
so that children can really

00:47:47.340 --> 00:47:49.940
get both parents,
and women can be

00:47:49.940 --> 00:47:52.520
able to do what they
want to do and not

00:47:52.520 --> 00:47:54.910
feel forced into part-time.

00:47:54.910 --> 00:47:56.852
GLORIA STEINEM: Yeah,
you put your finger--

00:47:56.852 --> 00:47:58.310
when I was talking
about redefining

00:47:58.310 --> 00:48:00.980
work, that was part of it.

00:48:00.980 --> 00:48:03.320
But we are at the
place you described.

00:48:03.320 --> 00:48:05.970
We have convinced the
majority of everybody

00:48:05.970 --> 00:48:09.990
that women can do what
men can do, which is huge.

00:48:09.990 --> 00:48:14.110
But we haven't even begun to
convince ourselves that men

00:48:14.110 --> 00:48:15.750
can do what women can do.

00:48:15.750 --> 00:48:18.660
And so children are growing
up with much too little father

00:48:18.660 --> 00:48:20.020
and too much mother.

00:48:20.020 --> 00:48:23.990
And men are not developing all
the qualities that are wrongly

00:48:23.990 --> 00:48:25.870
called feminine
but are just human,

00:48:25.870 --> 00:48:28.850
that are developed by
both raising children

00:48:28.850 --> 00:48:30.980
and being raised
to raise children,

00:48:30.980 --> 00:48:34.500
so that you become
a whole person.

00:48:34.500 --> 00:48:39.494
Much of it, I think,
is-- well, you

00:48:39.494 --> 00:48:40.910
don't know where
to begin exactly,

00:48:40.910 --> 00:48:42.076
so I won't say "much of it."

00:48:42.076 --> 00:48:46.430
But part of it is that
young women are not yet

00:48:46.430 --> 00:48:47.600
angry about this.

00:48:47.600 --> 00:48:50.340
I think that will be
the next big stage.

00:48:50.340 --> 00:48:54.780
Because women's pattern
of activism is usually--

00:48:54.780 --> 00:48:56.780
I'm sure everybody in
this room is an exception,

00:48:56.780 --> 00:49:00.100
but anyway-- is the reverse
of men's where we're

00:49:00.100 --> 00:49:01.550
conservative when we're young.

00:49:01.550 --> 00:49:03.096
We don't make waves
when we're young.

00:49:03.096 --> 00:49:05.220
And we get steadily more
radical and trouble-making

00:49:05.220 --> 00:49:07.090
as we get older.

00:49:07.090 --> 00:49:10.157
Whereas men tend to
be rebellious in youth

00:49:10.157 --> 00:49:11.240
and get more conservative.

00:49:11.240 --> 00:49:12.710
Because men gain power with age.

00:49:12.710 --> 00:49:14.080
Women lose power with age.

00:49:14.080 --> 00:49:16.150
It makes sense.

00:49:16.150 --> 00:49:20.340
Therefore, young women
are still assuming

00:49:20.340 --> 00:49:22.020
they have to do it all.

00:49:22.020 --> 00:49:23.750
And I must say, the
women's movement

00:49:23.750 --> 00:49:25.160
never said "have it all."

00:49:25.160 --> 00:49:28.380
We always knew that that was the
enemy of the women's movement

00:49:28.380 --> 00:49:28.880
saying that.

00:49:28.880 --> 00:49:31.171
If having it all means doing
it all, it's not possible.

00:49:31.171 --> 00:49:33.170
You can't have two
full-time jobs.

00:49:33.170 --> 00:49:39.450
So we need to start at
the microcosm of ourselves

00:49:39.450 --> 00:49:42.440
in the household saying no.

00:49:42.440 --> 00:49:44.460
Them what cooks can also eat.

00:49:44.460 --> 00:49:45.330
I'm not cooking.

00:49:48.200 --> 00:49:50.680
A woman in an audience
stood up and said that she

00:49:50.680 --> 00:49:51.670
was worried about this.

00:49:51.670 --> 00:49:55.477
So she just had a baby, and
she went away for three weeks

00:49:55.477 --> 00:49:57.060
and left her husband
with the new baby

00:49:57.060 --> 00:49:59.357
because she realized that
he would not learn unless he

00:49:59.357 --> 00:50:00.440
had to, just like she did.

00:50:00.440 --> 00:50:02.574
And the audience went-- [GASP]

00:50:02.574 --> 00:50:03.827
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:03.827 --> 00:50:05.285
ERIC SCHMIDT: And
did they survive?

00:50:05.285 --> 00:50:08.540
GLORIA STEINEM:
Yeah, they survived.

00:50:08.540 --> 00:50:10.850
Some of it is control.

00:50:10.850 --> 00:50:13.210
In women, it's the get out
of my kitchen syndrome.

00:50:13.210 --> 00:50:14.590
It's my house,
I'm going to cook.

00:50:14.590 --> 00:50:16.840
We have to look
at the microcosm,

00:50:16.840 --> 00:50:21.750
and are we really expecting
this kind of change?

00:50:21.750 --> 00:50:24.000
And we have to look
at the macrocosm

00:50:24.000 --> 00:50:28.660
and get work patterns that
allow both women and men to be

00:50:28.660 --> 00:50:31.520
the parents, the nurturing
parents, of babies

00:50:31.520 --> 00:50:32.640
and little children.

00:50:32.640 --> 00:50:35.080
So that you can work a three-day
week, or a shorter day,

00:50:35.080 --> 00:50:37.870
or what every other developed
country in the world

00:50:37.870 --> 00:50:41.830
has more than we do, which
are flexible work patterns

00:50:41.830 --> 00:50:42.980
and child care.

00:50:42.980 --> 00:50:44.870
We're the only
industrial democracy

00:50:44.870 --> 00:50:46.970
or whatever we are-- do
we still say "industrial"?

00:50:46.970 --> 00:50:48.040
No.

00:50:48.040 --> 00:50:48.900
"Technological"?

00:50:48.900 --> 00:50:49.809
Whatever we are.

00:50:49.809 --> 00:50:50.975
Do we still say "democracy"?

00:50:54.620 --> 00:50:57.190
Anyway, that doesn't have a
national system of child care.

00:50:57.190 --> 00:50:58.530
Kids need to see each other.

00:50:58.530 --> 00:51:00.321
They get very bored
with looking at grownup

00:51:00.321 --> 00:51:02.910
knees and the television set.

00:51:02.910 --> 00:51:05.760
So you can start at the
policy, political end,

00:51:05.760 --> 00:51:08.530
and you can start
at the personal end.

00:51:08.530 --> 00:51:10.589
And we'll meet in the
middle in a revolution.

00:51:10.589 --> 00:51:12.130
JANE FONDA: We could
take a good look

00:51:12.130 --> 00:51:14.180
at what the Netherlands does.

00:51:14.180 --> 00:51:16.334
They're not perfect, but
you're way ahead of us.

00:51:16.334 --> 00:51:18.500
ERIC SCHMIDT: We have time
for a few more questions.

00:51:18.500 --> 00:51:20.020
So why don't we have the
folks here, lined up,

00:51:20.020 --> 00:51:21.580
ask their questions
reasonably quickly.

00:51:21.580 --> 00:51:23.720
Go ahead, and we'll see you
get some quick answers as well.

00:51:23.720 --> 00:51:25.270
AUDIENCE: Well, I
wanted to tell you

00:51:25.270 --> 00:51:26.950
it's a pleasure
to have you here.

00:51:26.950 --> 00:51:29.300
And I thank you so
much for what you've

00:51:29.300 --> 00:51:35.050
done for everybody, especially
for me at Berkeley in the '70s.

00:51:35.050 --> 00:51:37.900
I wouldn't be here at
Google, I don't think,

00:51:37.900 --> 00:51:42.280
if I hadn't been
so taken by what

00:51:42.280 --> 00:51:46.980
you both did then, and stood up,
and gave us a voice and power.

00:51:46.980 --> 00:51:48.270
So I wanted to thank you.

00:51:48.270 --> 00:51:50.974
That was my first part.

00:51:50.974 --> 00:51:52.140
There's a couple more parts.

00:51:52.140 --> 00:51:55.080
One more part is
that if, somehow,

00:51:55.080 --> 00:51:57.360
you are partnering
with Google, I

00:51:57.360 --> 00:52:00.530
would be thrilled to help
you in some way to make

00:52:00.530 --> 00:52:02.910
the full circle to come back.

00:52:02.910 --> 00:52:08.820
I do QA, and I would be
glad to do some kind of QA.

00:52:08.820 --> 00:52:09.965
I would be thrilled.

00:52:09.965 --> 00:52:12.370
And then the third
part of it-- I

00:52:12.370 --> 00:52:15.580
know you touched upon
it with your question--

00:52:15.580 --> 00:52:21.520
is I am just really scared about
the rise of fundamentalism.

00:52:21.520 --> 00:52:23.590
It's not just one religion.

00:52:23.590 --> 00:52:25.470
We have it here in our country.

00:52:25.470 --> 00:52:30.850
And as a feminist, I am
so worried for the women

00:52:30.850 --> 00:52:32.970
who are oppressed again.

00:52:32.970 --> 00:52:35.990
We can have an influence
in our country,

00:52:35.990 --> 00:52:39.190
and hopefully, we'll stand up
and show the world something

00:52:39.190 --> 00:52:39.930
about it.

00:52:39.930 --> 00:52:41.410
But I do worry about that.

00:52:41.410 --> 00:52:44.760
And I was wondering
about your thoughts.

00:52:44.760 --> 00:52:46.400
GLORIA STEINEM:
Well, I don't know.

00:52:46.400 --> 00:52:50.920
Jane, do you want--
fundamentalism.

00:52:50.920 --> 00:52:54.570
Well, this is the point at
which I get in deep trouble, OK?

00:52:54.570 --> 00:52:56.514
But anyway.

00:52:56.514 --> 00:52:57.864
ERIC SCHMIDT: Please go ahead.

00:52:57.864 --> 00:52:59.780
AUDIENCE: And I'm not
picking on any religion.

00:52:59.780 --> 00:53:01.460
GLORIA STEINEM:
Monotheism was invented

00:53:01.460 --> 00:53:04.280
to put God into one
kind of human being,

00:53:04.280 --> 00:53:07.360
not into nature, to make
it OK to dominate nature,

00:53:07.360 --> 00:53:09.550
to make it OK to dominate women.

00:53:09.550 --> 00:53:12.610
The rise of fundamentalism
is precisely

00:53:12.610 --> 00:53:17.420
to put down the worldwide
rebellion of women,

00:53:17.420 --> 00:53:22.740
and it also has all
kinds of racial aspects.

00:53:22.740 --> 00:53:27.750
It is politics in
the sky, really.

00:53:27.750 --> 00:53:30.610
And the first thing I think
we have to do, especially

00:53:30.610 --> 00:53:34.190
in this country, is to stop
being afraid of discussing it.

00:53:34.190 --> 00:53:39.210
We have allowed religion
to be off-limits as an area

00:53:39.210 --> 00:53:42.630
of discussion because,
well, you know.

00:53:42.630 --> 00:53:45.130
But when it is political
and oppressive,

00:53:45.130 --> 00:53:47.200
we have to be able to name it.

00:53:47.200 --> 00:53:49.250
And that's what's so
great about Robin's book,

00:53:49.250 --> 00:53:52.780
because you see that
our founders were

00:53:52.780 --> 00:53:54.270
saying exactly that.

00:53:54.270 --> 00:53:56.680
You can't have a
democracy with priests.

00:53:56.680 --> 00:54:01.320
We shouldn't even have
chaplains in Congress.

00:54:01.320 --> 00:54:04.050
Jefferson sat in the White
House and edited everything

00:54:04.050 --> 00:54:07.050
undemocratic out of the Bible.

00:54:07.050 --> 00:54:11.190
Can you imagine anybody even
criticizing the Bible now?

00:54:11.190 --> 00:54:11.950
Saying, hello?

00:54:11.950 --> 00:54:14.430
Maybe the Gnostic Gospels
were much more authoritative.

00:54:14.430 --> 00:54:17.670
Jesus never said he
was the Son of God.

00:54:17.670 --> 00:54:21.710
There's a world there that
we are afraid to approach

00:54:21.710 --> 00:54:24.360
and therefore, is crushing
us, because it knows

00:54:24.360 --> 00:54:26.320
very well what its purpose is.

00:54:26.320 --> 00:54:28.537
And we're afraid to
name its purpose.

00:54:28.537 --> 00:54:29.370
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:54:29.370 --> 00:54:30.220
ERIC SCHMIDT: Let's go
to our next question.

00:54:30.220 --> 00:54:30.719
Thank you.

00:54:37.090 --> 00:54:40.200
AUDIENCE: So my mom was a member
of the National Organization

00:54:40.200 --> 00:54:44.260
of Women in the Mother's Day
march in Chicago in 1980,

00:54:44.260 --> 00:54:49.840
and did sit-ins in college,
and was taking action

00:54:49.840 --> 00:54:52.870
to support women's rights,
and thinks so highly of you

00:54:52.870 --> 00:54:54.810
both for all of your
action and leadership.

00:54:54.810 --> 00:54:57.585
And I don't see a
woman of my age doing

00:54:57.585 --> 00:54:59.410
that, including myself.

00:54:59.410 --> 00:55:00.970
And how did you
have the strength

00:55:00.970 --> 00:55:04.100
to take that leadership
role, and really

00:55:04.100 --> 00:55:06.306
put yourself out there,
and really message

00:55:06.306 --> 00:55:07.930
and communicate to
the public, and lead

00:55:07.930 --> 00:55:10.490
people to march and raise
awareness of these issues?

00:55:10.490 --> 00:55:13.530
Because I feel like we need
that now for women and men.

00:55:13.530 --> 00:55:15.970
And I see that there's
a leadership vacuum.

00:55:15.970 --> 00:55:17.600
And is it the media?

00:55:17.600 --> 00:55:21.090
And maybe if there was more
awareness of what was actually

00:55:21.090 --> 00:55:23.890
happening, people
would find a way

00:55:23.890 --> 00:55:27.500
to drive that anger and
frustration to actually doing

00:55:27.500 --> 00:55:28.350
something.

00:55:28.350 --> 00:55:31.920
Because in the last election, I
didn't go to whatever-- Ohio--

00:55:31.920 --> 00:55:32.760
and knock on doors.

00:55:32.760 --> 00:55:36.112
And I think a lot of people are
in this sort of complacency.

00:55:36.112 --> 00:55:38.760
I can't believe it, but I'm
not willing to do something.

00:55:38.760 --> 00:55:40.700
JANE FONDA: A lot of people did
though, go and knock on doors.

00:55:40.700 --> 00:55:41.320
AUDIENCE: Oh, they did?

00:55:41.320 --> 00:55:43.130
Yeah, and I hope in
the next election,

00:55:43.130 --> 00:55:45.550
I want to connect
with some group that

00:55:45.550 --> 00:55:46.760
is going to go and do that.

00:55:46.760 --> 00:55:49.220
But I feel like
that spirit was so

00:55:49.220 --> 00:55:51.827
alive in my parents'
generation in a way

00:55:51.827 --> 00:55:53.660
that I certainly didn't
see it on my college

00:55:53.660 --> 00:55:55.340
campus in Florida.

00:55:55.340 --> 00:55:57.690
And I don't know.

00:55:57.690 --> 00:56:03.580
How do we train the leaders
to really take that next--

00:56:03.580 --> 00:56:07.610
are you training new leaders?

00:56:07.610 --> 00:56:09.190
GLORIA STEINEM: We are training.

00:56:09.190 --> 00:56:12.545
The Women's Media Center
is-- the wonderful woman

00:56:12.545 --> 00:56:14.545
who was age 60, the one
who got up and said this

00:56:14.545 --> 00:56:15.860
is the first time she spoke.

00:56:15.860 --> 00:56:19.140
We're trying to help women
find their voices young,

00:56:19.140 --> 00:56:21.520
and get out there in the
media, and spread it.

00:56:21.520 --> 00:56:23.510
But I must say that
part of the reason

00:56:23.510 --> 00:56:26.910
you know Jane and me was
because there were so few of us.

00:56:26.910 --> 00:56:29.070
Now, it seems to me,
there's so many of you.

00:56:29.070 --> 00:56:30.930
We were like six crazy
people at the time.

00:56:30.930 --> 00:56:33.060
[LAUGHTER]

00:56:33.060 --> 00:56:38.130
And there are many,
many, many more now.

00:56:38.130 --> 00:56:43.640
And therefore, you don't see
the same kind of individuation.

00:56:43.640 --> 00:56:45.320
But it is present.

00:56:45.320 --> 00:56:47.310
It is absolutely present.

00:56:47.310 --> 00:56:53.210
And whether you're getting
politics in song lyrics

00:56:53.210 --> 00:56:54.670
with Ani DiFranco, whoever.

00:56:57.590 --> 00:57:00.090
That didn't exist before.

00:57:00.090 --> 00:57:01.550
With June Moon Honeymoon.

00:57:01.550 --> 00:57:07.500
Now you've got a CR
group just in your iPod.

00:57:07.500 --> 00:57:10.750
Or whether it's on campus
with the majority opinion.

00:57:10.750 --> 00:57:15.390
But it does require us to
say, how am I translating this

00:57:15.390 --> 00:57:16.347
into action?

00:57:16.347 --> 00:57:18.680
And what you just said was
the answer, that you're going

00:57:18.680 --> 00:57:19.796
to do it this time, right?

00:57:19.796 --> 00:57:20.920
ERIC SCHMIDT: That's right.

00:57:20.920 --> 00:57:22.520
Let's have a couple
more quickly,

00:57:22.520 --> 00:57:23.815
and then we'll be-- go ahead.

00:57:23.815 --> 00:57:25.440
AUDIENCE: Thank you
so much for coming.

00:57:25.440 --> 00:57:26.410
I'm just in awe.

00:57:26.410 --> 00:57:29.850
And I read every
bit of Ms. Magazine,

00:57:29.850 --> 00:57:31.780
and it really totally
changed my life.

00:57:31.780 --> 00:57:34.920
And just that you
came to Google,

00:57:34.920 --> 00:57:38.520
that we're not selling out,
and working for ourselves,

00:57:38.520 --> 00:57:42.490
that working for a corporation,
we could also work for a cause.

00:57:42.490 --> 00:57:44.170
So it means a lot to me.

00:57:44.170 --> 00:57:50.980
Anyway, my question was,
when I read feminism,

00:57:50.980 --> 00:57:53.520
sometimes, we have
to work with theory

00:57:53.520 --> 00:57:55.380
because we have to have vision.

00:57:55.380 --> 00:57:57.200
And it tends to be very white.

00:57:57.200 --> 00:58:01.310
And I grew up very sort of
white, so it speaks to me,

00:58:01.310 --> 00:58:05.770
but I really-- what is
your vision of feminism?

00:58:05.770 --> 00:58:08.000
Diverse yet very unified?

00:58:08.000 --> 00:58:10.690
Because I see it going
to environmentalism

00:58:10.690 --> 00:58:12.300
and all these other things.

00:58:12.300 --> 00:58:14.680
But what is your vision for now?

00:58:14.680 --> 00:58:18.732
And I'm fine with changes,
and I know visions change.

00:58:18.732 --> 00:58:20.940
But I would just like to
hear that since you're here,

00:58:20.940 --> 00:58:22.450
and I would like that slice.

00:58:22.450 --> 00:58:24.437
And thank you so
much for coming.

00:58:24.437 --> 00:58:25.520
GLORIA STEINEM: Thank you.

00:58:25.520 --> 00:58:27.686
JANE FONDA: I just want to
say one thing personally.

00:58:30.780 --> 00:58:34.230
I go to the Interdenominational
Theological Center in Atlanta.

00:58:34.230 --> 00:58:37.590
It's the largest training center
for African American ministers

00:58:37.590 --> 00:58:38.606
and me.

00:58:38.606 --> 00:58:40.840
[LAUGHTER]

00:58:40.840 --> 00:58:44.120
I'm the only white
student there.

00:58:44.120 --> 00:58:47.850
And a couple of the
classes that I'm taking

00:58:47.850 --> 00:58:50.620
is Womanist Interpretation.

00:58:50.620 --> 00:58:55.960
And I am in this school
surrounded by black--

00:58:55.960 --> 00:58:57.400
their word is womanist.

00:58:57.400 --> 00:59:04.360
It comes from Alice Walker's
writings, "My Mother's Garden."

00:59:04.360 --> 00:59:06.630
Feminism, womanism, it's there.

00:59:06.630 --> 00:59:08.620
And it's women of all color.

00:59:08.620 --> 00:59:11.560
And I personally
have experienced it.

00:59:11.560 --> 00:59:16.240
And it's proof to
me of how far we've

00:59:16.240 --> 00:59:20.500
come from an all-white,
middle class movement

00:59:20.500 --> 00:59:26.450
to a global, really
global, multiracial,

00:59:26.450 --> 00:59:29.680
multiethnicity movement.

00:59:29.680 --> 00:59:31.670
It's there.

00:59:31.670 --> 00:59:33.760
I just came back
from Sweden where

00:59:33.760 --> 00:59:36.750
there was a feminist
candidate running for office.

00:59:36.750 --> 00:59:39.540
And a bunch of us
went just to show

00:59:39.540 --> 00:59:43.670
that it's a global movement.

00:59:43.670 --> 00:59:45.340
GLORIA STEINEM: The
president of Liberia

00:59:45.340 --> 00:59:50.390
who basically won because
women in the marketplace

00:59:50.390 --> 00:59:51.680
could vote in the marketplace.

00:59:51.680 --> 00:59:55.660
And also because when they
couldn't reach an agreement,

00:59:55.660 --> 00:59:59.800
and it was mainly men reaching
an agreement-- the preface

00:59:59.800 --> 01:00:02.200
to the election-- the women
surrounded the building

01:00:02.200 --> 01:00:05.240
and wouldn't let them out.

01:00:05.240 --> 01:00:07.700
ERIC SCHMIDT: Let's
get our next question.

01:00:07.700 --> 01:00:09.530
AUDIENCE: Thank you
so much for coming.

01:00:09.530 --> 01:00:12.660
I'm a big believer in the
power of women's institutions.

01:00:12.660 --> 01:00:14.470
I went to an
undergraduate college that

01:00:14.470 --> 01:00:17.730
was an all-women
college and believe

01:00:17.730 --> 01:00:20.350
that women's groups have
been a big agent for change.

01:00:20.350 --> 01:00:22.280
But I struggle with
the idea that when

01:00:22.280 --> 01:00:25.360
you label something a women's
group, or women's media,

01:00:25.360 --> 01:00:27.290
that it gives more
credence to the idea

01:00:27.290 --> 01:00:30.940
that the mainstream
institution is still for men.

01:00:30.940 --> 01:00:34.099
It makes it easier to
belittle or sideline.

01:00:34.099 --> 01:00:36.640
So I'm just wondering how you
see the future of these groups,

01:00:36.640 --> 01:00:40.490
and how we can best integrate
our ideas into the mainstream.

01:00:40.490 --> 01:00:42.790
GLORIA STEINEM: Well, I
envision it like this.

01:00:42.790 --> 01:00:44.170
You've got a
powerful group here,

01:00:44.170 --> 01:00:45.870
you've got a less
powerful group here,

01:00:45.870 --> 01:00:51.540
whether it's because
of any reason-- gender,

01:00:51.540 --> 01:00:53.800
ethnicity, whatever it is.

01:00:53.800 --> 01:00:59.570
If you integrate at this point,
you come into a hierarchy.

01:00:59.570 --> 01:01:03.620
What you have to do is empower
this group to get up here,

01:01:03.620 --> 01:01:05.530
and then you can come together.

01:01:05.530 --> 01:01:10.420
So the coming together is the
goal, but the path to the goal

01:01:10.420 --> 01:01:15.210
is to become visible, to move
from the margins to the center,

01:01:15.210 --> 01:01:17.740
to have a voice,
to be able to say.

01:01:17.740 --> 01:01:21.960
So labeling things
in that way is

01:01:21.960 --> 01:01:26.050
a step towards not having
to label them eventually.

01:01:26.050 --> 01:01:29.330
And we need to keep saying
what the end goal is, I agree,

01:01:29.330 --> 01:01:32.490
so that we don't think that
separation is the goal.

01:01:32.490 --> 01:01:33.770
It is not.

01:01:33.770 --> 01:01:34.770
ERIC SCHMIDT: Thank you.

01:01:34.770 --> 01:01:36.957
And you will have the
honor of the last question.

01:01:36.957 --> 01:01:37.790
AUDIENCE: All right.

01:01:37.790 --> 01:01:40.700
I don't know whether I'm
thrilled or intimidated.

01:01:40.700 --> 01:01:43.330
But I want to say thank
you again for coming.

01:01:43.330 --> 01:01:46.444
I'm thrilled to be here
and hear the two of you.

01:01:46.444 --> 01:01:48.110
Actually, I want to
end this by bringing

01:01:48.110 --> 01:01:50.360
it closer to what I
think is something

01:01:50.360 --> 01:01:53.020
relevant to the women in this
audience, which is there's

01:01:53.020 --> 01:01:56.210
this brand new report out by
the National Academy of Sciences

01:01:56.210 --> 01:01:58.980
about women leadership in
science and engineering.

01:01:58.980 --> 01:02:00.920
And essentially
refuting everything

01:02:00.920 --> 01:02:04.810
that Larry Summers said,
and saying that it's not

01:02:04.810 --> 01:02:05.920
differences in ability.

01:02:05.920 --> 01:02:08.640
It's essentially the
death by a thousand cuts

01:02:08.640 --> 01:02:10.804
and the small little
things that happen

01:02:10.804 --> 01:02:12.470
to women over the
course of their career

01:02:12.470 --> 01:02:14.585
that end up holding them back.

01:02:14.585 --> 01:02:18.570
And the fact that we
have so many fewer women

01:02:18.570 --> 01:02:20.910
leaders in science and
technology than the pipeline

01:02:20.910 --> 01:02:23.270
would suggest.

01:02:23.270 --> 01:02:25.060
Many of the women
in this audience

01:02:25.060 --> 01:02:28.670
are living that pipeline,
living the route

01:02:28.670 --> 01:02:33.850
to potentially being a woman
leader in the sciences field.

01:02:33.850 --> 01:02:36.260
Do you have any
thoughts of this?

01:02:36.260 --> 01:02:38.720
How to overcome.

01:02:38.720 --> 01:02:42.590
How to stay steadfast through
these thousands of small things

01:02:42.590 --> 01:02:44.650
that aren't even noticed
by the participants,

01:02:44.650 --> 01:02:46.490
neither the men or the women.

01:02:46.490 --> 01:02:48.573
GLORIA STEINEM: She's
turning to me, the engineer.

01:02:49.630 --> 01:02:50.130
No.

01:02:50.130 --> 01:02:57.460
Well, I think you need
each others' support--

01:02:57.460 --> 01:03:00.315
women who are going through the
struggle, men who understand

01:03:00.315 --> 01:03:02.450
it and are supportive.

01:03:02.450 --> 01:03:03.820
We're communal creatures.

01:03:03.820 --> 01:03:06.220
If we're by ourselves,
we come to feel crazy,

01:03:06.220 --> 01:03:08.280
and alone, and immobilized.

01:03:08.280 --> 01:03:11.370
You need people to talk to about
what's happening to you once

01:03:11.370 --> 01:03:14.590
a week, once a month, get
together, call it whatever--

01:03:14.590 --> 01:03:18.100
a CR group, a networking group,
a book club, a quilting bee.

01:03:18.100 --> 01:03:20.410
I don't care what you
call it, but someplace

01:03:20.410 --> 01:03:22.830
where you can talk
about it, and get

01:03:22.830 --> 01:03:25.240
support, and pool information.

01:03:25.240 --> 01:03:30.060
I think that's
absolutely crucial.

01:03:30.060 --> 01:03:32.330
And then also, we need
to look at the way

01:03:32.330 --> 01:03:38.300
that the inclusion of other
groups transforms the outcome.

01:03:38.300 --> 01:03:42.410
There's a whole amazing feminist
critique of anthropology,

01:03:42.410 --> 01:03:45.140
and the feminist critique of
the scientific method that

01:03:45.140 --> 01:03:46.820
says, wait a minute,
your hypothesis

01:03:46.820 --> 01:03:47.890
dictates the whole thing.

01:03:47.890 --> 01:03:51.880
And what you get in the
laboratory is only replicate.

01:03:51.880 --> 01:03:54.240
All that argument,
which is fascinating.

01:03:54.240 --> 01:03:57.260
And we need to start our
own centers of power,

01:03:57.260 --> 01:03:58.610
like the Women's Media Center.

01:03:58.610 --> 01:04:02.510
My college, Smith College,
is the only women's college,

01:04:02.510 --> 01:04:04.690
I think, with an
engineering school.

01:04:04.690 --> 01:04:05.190
Why?

01:04:05.190 --> 01:04:08.710
Because the young women
were going to UMass,

01:04:08.710 --> 01:04:11.459
and were not getting
called on, and whatever.

01:04:11.459 --> 01:04:13.500
And this went on for years,
and years, and years.

01:04:13.500 --> 01:04:14.200
And they got pissed.

01:04:14.200 --> 01:04:16.075
And they started their
own engineering school

01:04:16.075 --> 01:04:18.940
on the premise that not
only would engineering

01:04:18.940 --> 01:04:22.230
change women-- to give
them knowledge, and power,

01:04:22.230 --> 01:04:24.510
and so on-- but women
would change engineering

01:04:24.510 --> 01:04:28.160
in all of its different
permutations and fields.

01:04:28.160 --> 01:04:33.880
So again, the environmentalists
are right-- act locally

01:04:33.880 --> 01:04:35.390
and think globally.

01:04:35.390 --> 01:04:38.060
It's starting with the
intimate, with ourselves,

01:04:38.060 --> 01:04:40.880
and keeping our strength up,
and keeping our vision up,

01:04:40.880 --> 01:04:46.540
and also going to change
the structure in the policy.

01:04:46.540 --> 01:04:49.760
ERIC SCHMIDT: Thank you so
much for taking the time

01:04:49.760 --> 01:04:51.300
to come here.

01:04:51.300 --> 01:04:53.080
In the last hour,
we've talked a lot

01:04:53.080 --> 01:04:55.890
about the sense of
activism and the role

01:04:55.890 --> 01:04:57.230
that everybody has played.

01:04:57.230 --> 01:05:00.306
But I could think of no
better examples of impact

01:05:00.306 --> 01:05:01.680
on the world than
the two of you.

01:05:01.680 --> 01:05:05.030
I think all of us can only hope
to have the level of impact

01:05:05.030 --> 01:05:06.480
on society as a
whole as you have

01:05:06.480 --> 01:05:11.626
done in the first two
of your three acts.

01:05:11.626 --> 01:05:15.410
And since it's going to get more
interesting as you get older,

01:05:15.410 --> 01:05:18.240
I'm very much looking
forward to their third act.

01:05:18.240 --> 01:05:19.250
Thank you very much.

01:05:19.250 --> 01:05:19.750
[APPLAUSE]

01:05:19.750 --> 01:05:21.650
GLORIA STEINEM: Thank you.

01:05:21.650 --> 01:05:23.500
JANE FONDA: Thank you.

